{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17653070","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17653070"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T21:42:23+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T21:42:23+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18560"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"18560","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/18560"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.05,0.91,0.05,0,0]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11292"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"114201"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"11292","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/11292"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18560"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"96201"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4930"},{"type":"tags","id":"4933"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"7094"},{"type":"tags","id":"8496"},{"type":"tags","id":"9927"},{"type":"tags","id":"10525"},{"type":"tags","id":"10526"},{"type":"tags","id":"10527"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"26187"},{"type":"contributions","id":"26192"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"114201","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/114201"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EThe nervous system control of urination (micturition) involves complex coordination between multiple regions of the central nervous system.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the role of the pontine micturition centre in voluntary urination?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Prevents bladder emptying during sleep","Coordinates bladder contraction and urethral sphincter relaxation","Maintains constant bladder tone","Senses bladder fullness directly","Controls involuntary urination only"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Ecoordination of bladder contraction and urethral sphincter relaxation\u003C/strong\u003E is the primary function of the pontine micturition centre. When appropriate social and environmental conditions exist, and the bladder is sufficiently full, the pontine micturition centre initiates synchronised detrusor muscle contraction and external urethral sphincter relaxation to allow controlled bladder emptying.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESenses bladder fullness directly\u003C/strong\u003E - bladder fullness is detected by stretch receptors in the bladder wall that signal to the sacral spinal cord. \u003Cstrong\u003EControls involuntary urination only\u003C/strong\u003E - the pontine centre is essential for voluntary control of micturition. \u003Cstrong\u003EMaintains constant bladder tone\u003C/strong\u003E - bladder tone varies with filling and is primarily controlled by local reflexes. \u003Cstrong\u003EPrevents bladder emptying during sleep\u003C/strong\u003E - this is controlled by higher centres in the cerebral cortex.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe pontine micturition centre receives input from both higher centres (for voluntary control) and the sacral spinal cord (sensing bladder fullness). It integrates these signals to determine when micturition should occur.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Voluntary control of micturition involves coordination between the pontine micturition centre and sacral spinal cord.","The pontine micturition centre initiates bladder contraction and urethral sphincter relaxation when appropriate.","Conscious control of micturition requires intact neural pathways between the cerebral cortex and brainstem."],"references":["Hall JE. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Philadelphia: Elsevier; 2021. Chapter 26; pg. 327.","Tortora GJ, Derrickson BH, Burkett B, Peoples G, Dye D, Cooke J, et al. Principles of Anatomy and Physiology, 2nd Asia-Pacific Edition: John Wiley \u0026 Sons, Limited; 2019"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"96201"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18560"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"96201","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/96201"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-09-15T13:19:16+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-09-15T13:19:16+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11292"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"114201"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"